00:37:35.250 --> 00:37:38.350
We don't do a lot of housework.

00:37:38.350 --> 00:37:38.850
Yes?

00:37:38.850 --> 00:37:41.300
AUDIENCE: So why do insects
still fly into the web?

00:37:41.300 --> 00:37:43.100
LESLIE BRUNETTA: Oh, so-- Right.

00:37:43.100 --> 00:37:47.950
So there-- maybe this isn't
the right metaphor to use.

00:37:47.950 --> 00:37:50.470
But there is this arms race
between the development

00:37:50.470 --> 00:37:55.610
of insect vision systems,
which are pretty amazing,

00:37:55.610 --> 00:37:58.390
and the optical qualities
of the-- let's see

00:37:58.390 --> 00:38:03.270
if I can also find
you a couple of-- OK.

00:38:03.270 --> 00:38:11.120
So for instance,
here's an orb web.

00:38:11.120 --> 00:38:17.540
The reflectance patterns
in the web, insects

00:38:17.540 --> 00:38:18.710
can actually learn.

00:38:18.710 --> 00:38:23.840
There have been-- my co-author
started some of this.

00:38:23.840 --> 00:38:27.260
There have been experiments that
show that flying insects can

00:38:27.260 --> 00:38:30.020
learn not to fly into webs.

00:38:30.020 --> 00:38:32.290
If they fly into one,
get stuck, and escape--

00:38:32.290 --> 00:38:34.630
which happens a lot--
they will-- most of them

00:38:34.630 --> 00:38:37.130
will not fly back
into the same web.

00:38:37.130 --> 00:38:39.890
There are some, she said, that
was almost sort of tragically

00:38:39.890 --> 00:38:42.690
comical, would keep
flying back in.

00:38:42.690 --> 00:38:45.770
But they will learn.

00:38:45.770 --> 00:38:48.506
But what happens is you can
see, even to the human eye,

00:38:48.506 --> 00:38:50.005
and obviously they
see differently--

00:38:50.005 --> 00:38:53.800
a bit differently than
we do, as that shifts,

00:38:53.800 --> 00:38:55.360
they're never static.

00:38:55.360 --> 00:38:57.130
Because the plants
that they're on

00:38:57.130 --> 00:38:59.040
are constantly
slightly shifting.

00:38:59.040 --> 00:39:02.010
And so you get these--
the pattern breaks up.

00:39:02.010 --> 00:39:04.910
And the insects work mainly
by pattern recognition.

00:39:04.910 --> 00:39:11.765
You also get-- this is the
web of a golden orb weaver.

00:39:11.765 --> 00:39:13.140
This happens to
be in Madagascar.

00:39:13.140 --> 00:39:16.230
But we have these in the
southern states also.

00:39:16.230 --> 00:39:18.450
You see how sort of
yellow and golden it is.

00:39:18.450 --> 00:39:20.009
AUDIENCE: About how big is that?

00:39:20.009 --> 00:39:21.550
LESLIE BRUNETTA:
That was really big.

00:39:21.550 --> 00:39:22.320
That was really big.

00:39:22.320 --> 00:39:24.180
AUDIENCE: So the spider
itself was a pretty good size?

00:39:24.180 --> 00:39:26.680
LESLIE BRUNETTA: About-- not
as big as you would think.

00:39:26.680 --> 00:39:27.390
About that big.

00:39:30.050 --> 00:39:31.040
So that's golden.

00:39:31.040 --> 00:39:36.364
Well, a lot of these insects
are looking for yellow flowers.

00:39:36.364 --> 00:39:37.280
AUDIENCE: It's a trap.

00:39:37.280 --> 00:39:39.410
LESLIE BRUNETTA: Yeah.

00:39:39.410 --> 00:39:42.810
And then here's
another example where

00:39:42.810 --> 00:39:44.930
there are a lot of insects.

00:39:44.930 --> 00:39:47.210
So you know Charlotte
in "Charlotte's Web"

00:39:47.210 --> 00:39:49.970
wrote in her web?

00:39:49.970 --> 00:39:52.350
He, White, got that
idea because there

00:39:52.350 --> 00:39:54.940
are lots of spiders that put
decorations in their webs.

00:39:54.940 --> 00:39:56.710
And it's still kind
of controversial

00:39:56.710 --> 00:39:59.990
exactly what those
decorations are about,

00:39:59.990 --> 00:40:07.620
whether they're predator
deterrence or prey attraction.

00:40:07.620 --> 00:40:11.690
But that's cribellate--
it's aciniform silk

00:40:11.690 --> 00:40:14.600
and sometimes cribellate silk
that they're putting on there.

00:40:14.600 --> 00:40:16.830
There's different
UV reflectance.

00:40:16.830 --> 00:40:20.790
And most insects
are attracted to UV,

00:40:20.790 --> 00:40:24.710
because there are UV
stripes often on plants

00:40:24.710 --> 00:40:27.630
leading to the
flower and also UV

00:40:27.630 --> 00:40:30.540
will often signal
to them open space.

00:40:30.540 --> 00:40:35.470
So in this particular
photograph,

00:40:35.470 --> 00:40:39.420
what she was trying to show
is that if you look on the--

00:40:39.420 --> 00:40:43.710
if you look down here,
this is a grass stock.

00:40:43.710 --> 00:40:45.800
And this is a UV photo.

00:40:45.800 --> 00:40:48.190
And the reflectance
of these decorations

00:40:48.190 --> 00:40:50.320
is quite similar
to the grass stock.

00:40:53.300 --> 00:40:57.560
So that's what's going
on, back and forth

00:40:57.560 --> 00:41:01.350
between the spiders
and the flying insects.

00:41:01.350 --> 00:41:01.850
Yes?

00:41:01.850 --> 00:41:04.183
AUDIENCE: I'm sort of surprised
that people would expect

00:41:04.183 --> 00:41:08.030
an answer to, is this predator
avoidance or prey attractance?

00:41:08.030 --> 00:41:12.602
Like it's something to help
the spider live longer.

00:41:12.602 --> 00:41:13.560
LESLIE BRUNETTA: Right.

00:41:13.560 --> 00:41:14.976
But it'll be both
of those things.

00:41:14.976 --> 00:41:17.187
But the interesting
question is--

00:41:17.187 --> 00:41:19.020
so there are a couple
interesting questions.

00:41:19.020 --> 00:41:22.070
One is it's a balance,
because their prey are

00:41:22.070 --> 00:41:25.660
arthropods with
arthropod vision systems,

00:41:25.660 --> 00:41:27.380
and their predators
are arthropods

00:41:27.380 --> 00:41:29.430
with arthropod vision systems.

00:41:29.430 --> 00:41:33.590
So there's this balance
between attracting prey and not

00:41:33.590 --> 00:41:35.780
attracting predators.

00:41:35.780 --> 00:41:38.040
I mean, there's a long way
to go before we figure out

00:41:38.040 --> 00:41:39.250
what's going on with this.

00:41:39.250 --> 00:41:41.820
And also, my suspicion,
just because there's

00:41:41.820 --> 00:41:46.540
such a huge-- thousands and
thousands of these species--

00:41:46.540 --> 00:41:48.690
it's probably different
in different cases,

00:41:48.690 --> 00:41:50.190
depending on where
they are and what

00:41:50.190 --> 00:41:53.760
the particular environment is.

00:41:53.760 --> 00:41:56.210
Yeah?

00:41:56.210 --> 00:41:59.640
AUDIENCE: For some
animals [INAUDIBLE]

00:41:59.640 --> 00:42:03.315
the other motivating factor
for changes in what they do

00:42:03.315 --> 00:42:04.540
is reproduction.

00:42:04.540 --> 00:42:08.950
Do spiders also do special
stuff with their--?

00:42:08.950 --> 00:42:12.370
LESLIE BRUNETTA:
Ah, spider sex is--

00:42:12.370 --> 00:42:15.910
so there are a couple of
things about spider sex.

00:42:15.910 --> 00:42:19.020
First of all, nobody
has quite figured out

00:42:19.020 --> 00:42:23.010
why they've evolved-- the males,
at the front of the spider's

00:42:23.010 --> 00:42:24.540
body there are pedipalps.

00:42:24.540 --> 00:42:27.100
And the males have
these modified feet

00:42:27.100 --> 00:42:30.040
called palpal organs.

00:42:30.040 --> 00:42:35.510
So what they do before they
mate, the male spiders go out.

00:42:35.510 --> 00:42:38.860
They go upside down, let's
say, between a couple

00:42:38.860 --> 00:42:40.070
of rocks or something.

00:42:40.070 --> 00:42:42.790
They spin a little web,
called a sperm web.

00:42:42.790 --> 00:42:45.600
Then they deposit
the sperm on the web.

00:42:45.600 --> 00:42:48.510
Then they suck the sperm
or draw the sperm up

00:42:48.510 --> 00:42:50.390
into these palpal organs.

00:42:50.390 --> 00:42:52.620
And then they go
looking for a female.

00:42:52.620 --> 00:42:54.770
And so these palpal
organs are what

00:42:54.770 --> 00:42:58.950
they insert into
the female spiders.

00:42:58.950 --> 00:43:03.660
So now there's also a
problem, because they're also

00:43:03.660 --> 00:43:06.030
very sexually
dimorphic, spiders.

00:43:06.030 --> 00:43:09.110
Which means that there's
a big difference in size.

00:43:09.110 --> 00:43:12.690
The females tend to be giant,
and the males tend to be tiny.

00:43:12.690 --> 00:43:17.480
And they tend-- this whole
idea that the females always

00:43:17.480 --> 00:43:19.410
eat the male is not true.

00:43:19.410 --> 00:43:22.430
Again, because there's
so many species,

00:43:22.430 --> 00:43:24.840
there's a huge variety
of things that happen.

00:43:24.840 --> 00:43:28.250
And so these mating practices
between different spiders

00:43:28.250 --> 00:43:30.160
are, like, all over the place.

00:43:30.160 --> 00:43:32.160
There's a certain
amount of cannibalism.

00:43:32.160 --> 00:43:35.740
There's a certain amount of-- I
forget the right term for this,

00:43:35.740 --> 00:43:38.490
but basically, the
palps go into the female

00:43:38.490 --> 00:43:41.390
and then break off, which
then prevents other males

00:43:41.390 --> 00:43:44.670
from inserting their palps.

00:43:44.670 --> 00:43:50.490
There are males who the
female will be on her web,

00:43:50.490 --> 00:43:54.610
and the male will figure out a
different pattern of vibrations

00:43:54.610 --> 00:43:57.110
to put on the web so that
she recognizes him as a male

00:43:57.110 --> 00:43:58.820
and not as prey.

00:43:58.820 --> 00:44:02.280
So there's-- that's a
whole other lecture.

00:44:02.280 --> 00:44:04.820
And actually, I don't--
I'm not an expert in that.

00:44:04.820 --> 00:44:07.168
But there are people who are.

00:44:07.168 --> 00:44:07.876
MALE SPEAKER: OK.

00:44:07.876 --> 00:44:10.100
Let's-- it's almost 2 o'clock.

00:44:10.100 --> 00:44:13.020
Let's thank Leslie
again for coming.

